The paper introduces a formalism for modeling strategic situations where two agents have misaligned objectives, and one agent has incomplete information about the true objective function. This involves modeling the situation as a zero-sum Markov game with one-sided incomplete information, which suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-categories of cs.GT (game theory) or cs.SY (systems and control). The paper also involves developing a computationally tractable algorithm to solve for equilibrium strategies, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.AI (artificial intelligence). Additionally, the paper involves extensive numerical simulation in a novel cyber security setting, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.CR (cryptography and security). Finally, the paper involves using recursive formulas to solve for equilibrium strategies, which suggests that it could belong to the sub-category of cs.LG (machine learning).
